# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sidechains
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Several Layer 2 solutions have been implemented as a result.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network allows near-instant, low-fee payments that settle on the Bitcoin base layer.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain built on top of Bitcoin which processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The block size limit, in concert with the proof-of-work difficulty adjustment settings of bitcoin's consensus protocol, constitutes a bottleneck in bitcoin's transaction processing capacity.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] This can result in increasing transaction fees and delayed processing of transactions that cannot be fit into a block.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Various proposals have come forth on how to scale bitcoin, and a contentious debate has resulted.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Technical optimizations may decrease the amount of computing resources required to receive, process and record bitcoin transactions, allowing increased throughput without placing extra demand on the bitcoin network.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] These modifications can be to either the network, in which case a fork is required, or to individual node software (such as Bitcoin Core).
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network (LN) is a protocol that aims to improve bitcoin's scalability and speed without sacrificing trustless operation.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The Lightning Network requires putting a funding transaction on the blockchain to open a payment channel.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Once a channel is opened, connected participants are able to make rapid payments within the channel or may route payments by "hopping" between channels at intermediate nodes for little to no fee.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2018 Blockstream launched a payment processing system for web retailers called "Lightning Charge", noted that lightning was live on mainnet with 200 nodes operating as of 27 January 2018 and advised it should still be considered "in testing".
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The Liquid Network is a sidechain that Blockstream developed which is built on top of Bitcoin.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] It processes blocks every minute instead of every 10 minutes.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] On 15 March 2018, Lightning Labs released the beta version of its lnd Lightning Network implementation for bitcoin mainnet, and on 28 March 2018, ACINQ released a mainnet beta of its eclair implementation and desktop application.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] In January 2019 the online retailer Bitrefill announced that it receives more payments in Bitcoin via the lightning network than any other cryptocurrency they accept.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] In June 2021, the Legislative Assembly of El Salvador voted legislation to make Bitcoin legal tender in El Salvador.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The decision was based on the success of the Bitcoin Beach ecosystem in El Zonte that used a LN based wallet.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] The government will be introducing a wallet utilising the Lightning Network protocol while giving the freedom for citizens to use other Bitcoin Lightning wallets.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] In 2025, El Salvador's bitcoin project was discontinued as a whole.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin has a block time of 10 minutes and a block size of 1 MB.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Various increases to this limit, and proposals to remove it completely, have been proposed over bitcoin's history.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Implementing any of these proposals involves a fork.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Litecoin produces blocks four times faster than Bitcoin which leads to a 4x improvement in throughput.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Dogecoin has even more throughput with a block time of 1 minute.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin Cash has a block size of 32 MB and hence 32x more throughput than Bitcoin.
[src:sidechains/bitcoin-scalability] Bitcoin SV removed the block size limit altogether.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A **blockchain** is a distributed ledger with growing lists of records (*blocks*) that are securely linked together via cryptographic hashes.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Each block contains a cryptographic hash of the previous block, a timestamp, and transaction data (generally represented as a Merkle tree, where data nodes are represented by leaves).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Since each block contains information about the previous block, they effectively form a *chain* (*viz.* linked list data structure), with each additional block linking to the ones before it.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Consequently, blockchain transactions are resistant to alteration because, once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be changed retroactively without altering all subsequent blocks and obtaining network consensus to accept these changes.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchains are typically managed by a peer-to-peer (P2P) computer network for use as a public distributed ledger, where nodes collectively adhere to a consensus algorithm protocol to add and validate new transaction blocks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Although blockchain records are not unalterable, since blockchain forks are possible, blockchains may be considered secure by design and exemplify a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A blockchain was created by a person (or group of people) using the name (or pseudonym) Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008 to serve as the public distributed ledger for bitcoin cryptocurrency transactions, based on previous work by Stuart Haber, W.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The implementation of the blockchain within bitcoin made it the first digital currency to solve the double-spending problem without the need for a trusted authority or central server.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The bitcoin design has inspired other applications and blockchains that are readable by the public and are widely used by cryptocurrencies.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The blockchain may be considered a type of payment rail.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Private blockchains have been proposed for business use.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] *Computerworld* called the marketing of such privatized blockchains without a proper security model "snake oil"; however, others have argued that permissioned blockchains, if carefully designed, may be more decentralized and therefore more secure in practice than permissionless ones.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Cryptographer David Chaum first proposed a blockchain-like protocol in his 1982 dissertation "Computer Systems Established, Maintained, and Trusted by Mutually Suspicious Groups".
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Further work on a cryptographically secured chain of blocks was described in 1991 by Stuart Haber and W.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] They wanted to implement a system wherein document timestamps could not be tampered with.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 1992, Haber, Stornetta, and Dave Bayer incorporated Merkle trees into the design, which improved its efficiency by allowing several document certificates to be collected into one block.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Under their company Surety, their document certificate hashes have been published in *The New York Times* every week since 1995.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The first decentralized blockchain was conceptualized by a person (or group of people) known as Satoshi Nakamoto in 2008.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Nakamoto improved the design in an important way using a Hashcash-like method to timestamp blocks without requiring them to be signed by a trusted party and introducing a difficulty parameter to stabilize the rate at which blocks are added to the chain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The design was implemented the following year by Nakamoto as a core component of the cryptocurrency bitcoin, where it serves as the public ledger for all transactions on the network.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In August 2014, the bitcoin blockchain file size, containing records of all transactions that have occurred on the network, reached 20 GB (gigabytes).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] By 2024, the bitcoin blockchain exceeded 600 GB.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The words *block* and *chain* were used separately in Satoshi Nakamoto's original paper, but were eventually popularized as a single word, *blockchain*, by 2016.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] According to Accenture, an application of the diffusion of innovations theory suggests that blockchains attained a 13.5% adoption rate within financial services in 2016, therefore reaching the early adopters' phase.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Industry trade groups joined to create the Global Blockchain Forum in 2016, an initiative of the Chamber of Digital Commerce.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In May 2018, Gartner found that only 1% of CIOs indicated any kind of blockchain adoption within their organisations, and only 8% of CIOs were in the short-term "planning or [looking at] active experimentation with blockchain".
[src:sidechains/blockchain] For the year 2019 Gartner reported 5% of CIOs believed blockchain technology was a 'game-changer' for their business.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A blockchain is a decentralized, distributed, and often public, digital ledger consisting of records called *blocks* that are used to record transactions across many computers so that any involved block cannot be altered retroactively, without the alteration of all subsequent blocks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This allows the participants to verify and audit transactions independently and relatively inexpensively.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A blockchain database is managed autonomously using a peer-to-peer network and a distributed timestamping server.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] They are authenticated by mass collaboration powered by collective self-interests.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Such a design facilitates robust workflow where participants' uncertainty regarding data security is marginal.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The use of a blockchain removes the characteristic of infinite reproducibility from a digital asset.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] It confirms that each unit of value was transferred only once, solving the long-standing problem of double-spending.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A blockchain has been described as a *value-exchange protocol*.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blocks hold batches of valid transactions that are hashed and encoded into a Merkle tree.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Each block includes the cryptographic hash of the prior block in the blockchain, linking the two.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This iterative process confirms the integrity of the previous block, all the way back to the initial block, which is known as the *genesis block* (Block 0).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] To assure the integrity of a block and the data contained in it, the block is usually digitally signed.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Sometimes separate blocks can be produced concurrently, creating a temporary fork.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In addition to a secure hash-based history, any blockchain has a specified algorithm for scoring different versions of the history so that one with a higher score can be selected over others.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blocks not selected for inclusion in the chain are called orphan blocks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Peers supporting the database have different versions of the history from time to time.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] They keep only the highest-scoring version of the database known to them.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Whenever a peer receives a higher-scoring version (usually the old version with a single new block added) they extend or overwrite their own database and retransmit the improvement to their peers.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] There is never an absolute guarantee that any particular entry will remain in the best version of history forever.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchains are typically built to add the score of new blocks onto old blocks and are given incentives to extend with new blocks rather than overwrite old blocks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Therefore, the probability of an entry becoming superseded decreases exponentially as more blocks are built on top of it, eventually becoming very low.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] For example, bitcoin uses a proof-of-work system, where the chain with the most cumulative proof-of-work is considered the valid one by the network.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] There are a number of methods that can be used to demonstrate a sufficient level of computation.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Within a blockchain the computation is carried out redundantly rather than in the traditional segregated and parallel manner.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The *block time* is the average time it takes for the network to generate one extra block in the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] By the time of block completion, the included data becomes verifiable.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In cryptocurrency, this is practically when the transaction takes place, so a shorter block time means faster transactions.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Since 2022, the block time for Ethereum is set to exactly 12 seconds, while for bitcoin it is on average 10 minutes.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A *hard fork* is a change to the blockchain protocol that is not backward compatible and requires all users to upgrade their software in order to continue participating in the network.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In a hard fork, the network splits into two separate versions: one that follows the new rules and one that follows the old rules.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] For example, Ethereum was hard forked in 2016 to "make whole" the investors in The DAO, which had been hacked by exploiting a vulnerability in its code.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In this case, the fork resulted in a split creating Ethereum and Ethereum Classic chains.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2014, the Nxt community was asked to consider a hard fork that would have led to a rollback of the blockchain records to mitigate the effects of a theft of 50 million NXT from a major cryptocurrency exchange.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The hard fork proposal was rejected, and some of the funds were recovered after negotiations and ransom payment.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Alternatively, to prevent a permanent split, a majority of nodes using the new software may return to the old rules, as was the case with Bitcoin split on 12 March 2013.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A more recent hard-fork example is of Bitcoin in 2017, which resulted in a split creating Bitcoin Cash.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The network split was mainly due to a disagreement in how to increase the transactions per second to accommodate for demand.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] By storing data across its peer-to-peer network, the blockchain eliminates some risks that come with data being held centrally.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The decentralized blockchain may use ad hoc message passing and distributed networking.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In a so-called "51% attack" a central entity gains control of more than half of a network and can then manipulate that specific blockchain record at will, allowing double-spending.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain security methods include the use of public-key cryptography.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A *public key* (a long, random-looking string of numbers) is an address on the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Value tokens sent across the network are recorded as belonging to that address.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A *private key* is like a password that gives its owner access to their digital assets or the means to otherwise interact with the various capabilities that blockchains now support.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Data stored on the blockchain is generally considered incorruptible.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Every node in a decentralized system has a copy of the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Data quality is maintained by massive database replication and computational trust.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] No centralized "official" copy exists and no user is "trusted" more than any other.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Transactions are broadcast to the network using the software.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Messages are delivered on a best-effort basis.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Early blockchains rely on energy-intensive mining nodes to validate transactions, add them to the block they are building, and then broadcast the completed block to other nodes.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchains use various time-stamping schemes, such as proof-of-work, to serialize changes.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Later consensus methods include proof of stake.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The growth of a decentralized blockchain is accompanied by the risk of centralization because the computer resources required to process larger amounts of data become more expensive.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Finality is the level of confidence that the well-formed block recently appended to the blockchain will not be revoked in the future (is "finalized") and thus can be trusted.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Byzantine fault tolerance-based proof-of-stake protocols purport to provide so called "absolute finality": a randomly chosen validator proposes a block, the rest of validators vote on it, and, if a supermajority decision approves it, the block is irreversibly committed into the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A modification of this method, an "economic finality", is used in practical protocols, like the Casper protocol used in Ethereum: validators which sign two different blocks at the same position in the blockchain are subject to "slashing", where their leveraged stake is forfeited.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Open blockchains are more user-friendly than some traditional ownership records, which, while open to the public, still require physical access to view.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Because all early blockchains were permissionless, controversy has arisen over the blockchain definition.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] An issue in this ongoing debate is whether a private system with verifiers tasked and authorized (permissioned) by a central authority should be considered a blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Proponents of permissioned or private chains argue that the term "blockchain" may be applied to any **data structure** that batches data into time-stamped blocks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] These blockchains serve as a distributed version of multiversion concurrency control (MVCC) in databases.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Just as MVCC prevents two transactions from concurrently modifying a single object in a database, blockchains prevent two transactions from spending the same single output in a blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Opponents say that permissioned systems resemble traditional corporate databases, not supporting decentralized data verification, and that such systems are not hardened against operator tampering and revision.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] An advantage to an open, permissionless, or public, blockchain network is that guarding against bad actors is not required and no access control is needed.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This means that applications can be added to the network without the approval or trust of others, using the blockchain as a transport layer.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Bitcoin and other cryptocurrencies currently secure their blockchain by requiring new entries to include proof of work.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] To prolong the blockchain, bitcoin uses Hashcash puzzles.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] While Hashcash was designed in 1997 by Adam Back, the original idea was first proposed by Cynthia Dwork and Moni Naor and Eli Ponyatovski in their 1992 paper "Pricing via Processing or Combatting Junk Mail".
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2016, venture capital investment for blockchain-related projects was weakening in the US but increasing in China.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Bitcoin and many other cryptocurrencies use open (public) blockchains.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] As of April 2018, bitcoin has the highest market capitalization.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Permissioned blockchains use an access control layer to govern who has access to the network.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] It has been argued that permissioned blockchains can guarantee a certain level of decentralization, if carefully designed, as opposed to permissionless blockchains, which are often centralized in practice.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Nikolai Hampton argued in *Computerworld* that "There is also no need for a '51 percent' attack on a private blockchain, as the private blockchain (most likely) already controls 100 percent of all block creation resources.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] It's unlikely that any private blockchain will try to protect records using gigawatts of computing power — it's time-consuming and expensive." He also said, "Within a private blockchain there is also no 'race'; there's no incentive to use more power or discover blocks faster than competitors.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The analysis of public blockchains has become increasingly important with the popularity of bitcoin, Ethereum, litecoin and other cryptocurrencies.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A blockchain, if it is public, provides access to anyone to observe and analyse the chain data, given the know-how.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The process of understanding and accessing the flow of crypto has been an issue for many cryptocurrencies, crypto exchanges and banks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The reason for this is accusations of blockchain-enabled cryptocurrencies enabling illicit dark market trading of drugs, weapons, money laundering, etc.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A common belief has been that cryptocurrency is private and untraceable, thus leading many actors to use it for illegal purposes.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This is changing now that specialised tech companies provide blockchain tracking services, making crypto exchanges, law-enforcement and banks more aware of what is happening with crypto funds and fiat-crypto exchanges.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The development, some argue, has led criminals to prioritise the use of new cryptos such as Monero.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In April 2016, Standards Australia submitted a proposal to the International Organization for Standardization to consider developing standards to support blockchain technology.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This proposal resulted in the creation of ISO Technical Committee 307, Blockchain and Distributed Ledger Technologies.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The technical committee has working groups relating to blockchain terminology, reference architecture, security and privacy, identity, smart contracts, governance and interoperability for blockchain and DLT, as well as standards specific to industry sectors and generic government requirements.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Many other national standards bodies and open standards bodies are also working on blockchain standards.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Although most of blockchain implementation are decentralized and distributed, Oracle launched a centralized blockchain table feature in Oracle 21c database.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The Blockchain Table in Oracle 21c database is a centralized blockchain which provide immutable feature.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Compared to decentralized blockchains, centralized blockchains normally can provide a higher throughput and lower latency of transactions than consensus-based distributed blockchains.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Currently, there are at least four types of blockchain networks — public blockchains, private blockchains, consortium blockchains and hybrid blockchains.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A public blockchain has no access restrictions.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Anyone with an Internet connection can send transactions to it as well as become a validator (i.e., participate in the execution of a consensus protocol).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Usually, such networks offer economic incentives for those who secure them and utilize some type of a proof-of-stake or proof-of-work algorithm.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Some of the largest, most known public blockchains are the bitcoin blockchain and the Ethereum blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] One cannot join it unless invited by the network administrators.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Participant and validator access is restricted.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] To distinguish between open blockchains and other peer-to-peer decentralized database applications that are not open ad-hoc compute clusters, the terminology Distributed Ledger (DLT) is normally used for private blockchains.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A hybrid blockchain has a combination of centralized and decentralized features.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The exact workings of the chain can vary based on which portions of centralization and decentralization are used.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A sidechain is a designation for a blockchain ledger that runs in parallel to a primary blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A consortium blockchain is a type of blockchain that combines elements of both public and private blockchains.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In a consortium blockchain, a group of organizations come together to create and operate the blockchain, rather than a single entity.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The consortium members jointly manage the blockchain network and are responsible for validating transactions.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are permissioned, meaning that only certain individuals or organizations are allowed to participate in the network.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This allows for greater control over who can access the blockchain and helps to ensure that sensitive information is kept confidential.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Consortium blockchains are commonly used in industries where multiple organizations need to collaborate on a common goal, such as supply chain management or financial services.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] One advantage of consortium blockchains is that they can be more efficient and scalable than public blockchains, as the number of nodes required to validate transactions is typically smaller.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Additionally, consortium blockchains can provide greater security and reliability than private blockchains, as the consortium members work together to maintain the network.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Some examples of consortium blockchains include Quorum and Hyperledger.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The primary use of blockchains is as a distributed ledger for cryptocurrencies such as bitcoin; there were also a few other operational products that had matured from proof of concept by late 2016.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] As of 2016, some businesses have been testing the technology and conducting low-level implementation to gauge blockchain's effects on organizational efficiency in their back office.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2019, it was estimated that around $2.9 billion were invested in blockchain technology, which represents an 89% increase from the year prior.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A report from to PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) in 2021 said that blockchain technology had the potential to generate an annual business value of more than $3 trillion by 2030.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] PwC surveyed 600 business executives and determined that 84% have at least some exposure to utilizing blockchain technology.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2019, the BBC World Service radio and podcast series *50 Things That Made the Modern Economy* identified blockchain as a technology that would have far-reaching consequences for economics and society.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The economist and *Financial Times* journalist and broadcaster Tim Harford discussed why the underlying technology might have much wider applications and the challenges that needed to be overcome.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] His first broadcast was on 29 June 2019.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Most cryptocurrencies are designed to gradually decrease the production of that currency, placing a cap on the total amount of that currency that will ever be in circulation.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Compared with ordinary currencies held by financial institutions or kept as cash on hand, cryptocurrencies can be more difficult for seizure by law enforcement.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The validity of each cryptocurrency's coins is provided by a blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A blockchain is a continuously growing list of records, called blocks, which are linked and secured using cryptography.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Each block typically contains a hash pointer as a link to a previous block, a timestamp and transaction data.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] By design, blockchains are inherently resistant to modification of the data.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] It is "an open, distributed ledger that can record transactions between two parties efficiently and in a verifiable and permanent way".
[src:sidechains/blockchain] For use as a distributed ledger, a blockchain is typically managed by a peer-to-peer network collectively adhering to a protocol for validating new blocks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Once recorded, the data in any given block cannot be altered retroactively without the alteration of all subsequent blocks, which requires collusion of the network majority.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchains are secure by design and are an example of a distributed computing system with high Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Decentralized consensus has therefore been achieved with a blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In the context of cryptocurrencies, the blockchain serves as a public ledger for all transactions.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Cryptocurrencies use various timestamping schemes to "prove the validity of transactions added to the blockchain ledger without the need for a trusted third party".
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The first cryptocurrency was Bitcoin, which was first released as open-source software in 2009.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] As cryptocurrencies have gained prominence, several countries have made advancements in their private and commercial law treatment to address legal uncertainties.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In the United States, for example, the 2022 amendments to the Uniform Commercial Code (UCC) introduced Article 12, which establishes "controllable electronic records" (CERs) as a new category of personal property.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This framework provides legal clarity for the ownership, transfer, and use of cryptocurrencies as CERs, with the concept of "control" serving as a functional equivalent to possession for digital assets.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] These reforms aim to align legal standards with market practices, reducing title disputes and supporting the integration of cryptocurrencies into commercial transactions.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain-based smart contracts are contracts that can be partially or fully executed or enforced without human interaction.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] One of the main objectives of a smart contract is automated escrow.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A key feature of smart contracts is that they do not need a trusted third party (such as a trustee) to act as an intermediary between contracting entities — the blockchain network executes the contract on its own.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This may reduce friction between entities when transferring value and could subsequently open the door to a higher level of transaction automation.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] An IMF staff discussion from 2018 reported that smart contracts based on blockchain technology might reduce moral hazards and optimize the use of contracts in general, but "no viable smart contract systems have yet emerged." Due to the lack of widespread use, their legal status was unclear.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] According to *Reason* in 2016, many banks have expressed interest in implementing distributed ledgers for use in banking and are cooperating with companies creating private blockchains.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] According to a September 2016 IBM study, this implementation was occurring faster than expected.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain technology has been proposed as a way to speed up back office settlement systems.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2017, UBS opened a lab dedicated to researching how blockchain technology could be used in financial services.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2017, the German bank Berenberg described blockchain as an "overhyped technology" that has had a large number of "proofs of concept", but still has major challenges, and very few success stories.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain technology has allowed for new forms of fundraising such as initial coin offerings (ICOs) and security token offerings (STOs), also sometimes referred to as digital security offerings (DSOs).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] STO/DSOs may be conducted privately or on public, regulated stock exchange and are used to tokenize assets such as company shares, intellectual property, real estate, and others.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain technology, such as cryptocurrencies and non-fungible tokens (NFTs), has been used in video games for monetization.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Many live-service games offer in-game customization options, such as character skins or other in-game items, which the players can earn and trade with other players using in-game currency.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain games typically allow players to trade these in-game items for cryptocurrency, which can then be exchanged for money.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The first known game to use blockchain technologies was *CryptoKitties*, launched in November 2017, where the player would purchase NFTs with Ethereum cryptocurrency, each NFT consisting of a virtual pet that the player could breed with others to create offspring with combined traits as new NFTs.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The game made headlines in December 2017 when one virtual pet sold for more than US$100,000.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] *CryptoKitties* also illustrated scalability problems for games on Ethereum when it created significant congestion on the Ethereum network in early 2018 with approximately 30% of all Ethereum transactions being for the game.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] By the early 2020s, there had not been a breakout success in video games using blockchain, as these games tend to focus on using blockchain for speculation instead of more traditional forms of gameplay, which offers limited appeal to most players.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Such games also represent a high risk to investors as their revenues can be difficult to predict.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Several major publishers, including Ubisoft, Electronic Arts, and Take Two Interactive, have stated that blockchain and NFT-based games are under serious consideration for their companies in the future.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Valve's prior history with gambling, specifically skin gambling, was speculated to be a factor in the decision to ban blockchain games.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] There have been several different efforts to employ blockchains in supply chain management.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] There are several different efforts to offer domain name services via the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] These domain names can be controlled by the use of a private key, which purports to allow for uncensorable websites.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] This would also bypass a registrar's ability to suppress domains used for fraud, abuse, or illegal content.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Namecoin is a cryptocurrency that supports the ".bit" top-level domain (TLD).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Namecoin was forked from bitcoin in 2011.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The .bit TLD is not sanctioned by ICANN, instead requiring an alternative DNS root.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] As of 2015, .bit was used by 28 websites, out of 120,000 registered names.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Namecoin was dropped by OpenNIC in 2019, due to malware and potential other legal issues.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Other blockchain alternatives to ICANN include *The Handshake Network*, *EmerDNS*, and *Unstoppable Domains*.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Specific TLDs include ".eth", ".luxe", and ".kred", which are associated with the Ethereum blockchain through the Ethereum Name Service (ENS).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The .kred TLD also acts as an alternative to conventional cryptocurrency wallet addresses as a convenience for transferring cryptocurrency.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain technology can be used to create a permanent, public, transparent ledger system for compiling data on sales, tracking digital use and payments to content creators, such as wireless users or musicians.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The Gartner 2019 CIO Survey reported 2% of higher education respondents had launched blockchain projects and another 18% were planning academic projects in the next 24 months.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2017, IBM partnered with ASCAP and PRS for Music to adopt blockchain technology in music distribution.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] New distribution methods are available for the insurance industry such as peer-to-peer insurance, parametric insurance and microinsurance following the adoption of blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The sharing economy and IoT are also set to benefit from blockchains because they involve many collaborating peers.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The use of blockchain in libraries is being studied with a grant from the U.S.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Institute of Museum and Library Services.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Other blockchain designs include Hyperledger, a collaborative effort from the Linux Foundation to support blockchain-based distributed ledgers, with projects under this initiative including Hyperledger Burrow (by Monax) and Hyperledger Fabric (spearheaded by IBM).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Another is Quorum, a permissioned private blockchain by JPMorgan Chase with private storage, used for contract applications.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Oracle introduced a blockchain table feature in its Oracle 21c database.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain is also being used in peer-to-peer energy trading.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain could be used in detecting counterfeits by associating unique identifiers to products, documents and shipments, and storing records associated with transactions that cannot be forged or altered.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] It is however argued that blockchain technology needs to be supplemented with technologies that provide a strong binding between physical objects and blockchain systems, as well as provisions for content creator verification *ala* KYC standards.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The EUIPO established an Anti-Counterfeiting Blockathon Forum, with the objective of "defining, piloting and implementing" an anti-counterfeiting infrastructure at the European level.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The Dutch Standardisation organisation NEN uses blockchain together with QR Codes to authenticate certificates.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Beijing and Shanghai are among the cities designated by China to trial blockchain applications as January 30, 2022.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In Chinese legal proceedings, blockchain technology was first accepted as a method for authenticating internet evidence by the Hangzhou Internet Court in 2019 and has since been accepted by other Chinese courts.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] With the increasing number of blockchain systems appearing, even only those that support cryptocurrencies, blockchain interoperability is becoming a topic of major importance.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The objective is to support transferring assets from one blockchain system to another blockchain system.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Wegner stated that "interoperability is the ability of two or more software components to cooperate despite differences in language, interface, and execution platform".
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The objective of blockchain interoperability is therefore to support such cooperation among blockchain systems, despite those kinds of differences.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] There are already several blockchain interoperability solutions available.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] They can be classified into three categories: cryptocurrency interoperability approaches, blockchain engines, and blockchain connectors.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Several individual IETF participants produced the draft of a blockchain interoperability architecture.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Some cryptocurrencies use blockchain mining, namely the peer-to-peer computer computations by which transactions are validated and verified.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In June 2018, the Bank for International Settlements criticized the use of public proof-of-work blockchains for their high energy consumption.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Early concern over the high energy consumption was a factor in later blockchains such as Cardano (2017), Solana (2020) and Polkadot (2020) adopting the less energy-intensive proof-of-stake model.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Researchers have estimated that bitcoin consumes 100,000 times as much energy as proof-of-stake networks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In 2021, a study by Cambridge University determined that bitcoin (at 121 terawatt-hours per year) used more electricity than Argentina (at 121TWh) and the Netherlands (109TWh).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] According to Digiconomist, one bitcoin transaction required 708 kilowatt-hours of electrical energy, the amount an average U.S. household consumed in 24 days.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Treasury secretary Janet Yellen called bitcoin "an extremely inefficient way to conduct transactions", saying "the amount of energy consumed in processing those transactions is staggering".
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Nicholas Weaver, of the International Computer Science Institute at the University of California, Berkeley, examined blockchain's online security, and the energy efficiency of proof-of-work public blockchains, and in both cases found it grossly inadequate.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The 31TWh-45TWh of electricity used for bitcoin in 2018 produced 17–23 million tonnes of CO2.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] By 2022, the University of Cambridge and Digiconomist estimated that the two largest proof-of-work blockchains, bitcoin and Ethereum, together used twice as much electricity in one year as the whole of Sweden, leading to the release of up to 120 million tonnes of CO2 each year.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Some cryptocurrency developers are considering moving from the proof-of-work model to the proof-of-stake model.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In Sept, 2022, Ethereum converted from proof-of-work to proof-of-stake.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In October 2014, the MIT Bitcoin Club, with funding from MIT alumni, provided undergraduate students at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology access to $100 of bitcoin.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The adoption rates, as studied by Catalini and Tucker (2016), revealed that when people who typically adopt technologies early are given delayed access, they tend to reject the technology.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Many universities have founded departments focusing on crypto and blockchain, including MIT, in 2017.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In the same year, Edinburgh became "one of the first big European universities to launch a blockchain course", according to the *Financial Times*.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Motivations for adopting blockchain technology (an aspect of innovation adoption) have been investigated by researchers.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] For example, Janssen, et al. provided a framework for analysis, and Koens & Poll pointed out that adoption could be heavily driven by non-technical factors.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Based on behavioral models, Li has discussed the differences between adoption at the individual level and organizational levels.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Scholars in business and management have started studying the role of blockchains to support collaboration.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] It has been argued that blockchains can foster both cooperation (i.e., prevention of opportunistic behavior) and coordination (i.e., communication and information sharing).
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Thanks to reliability, transparency, traceability of records, and information immutability, blockchains facilitate collaboration in a way that differs both from the traditional use of contracts and from relational norms.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Contrary to contracts, blockchains do not directly rely on the legal system to enforce agreements.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In addition, contrary to the use of relational norms, blockchains do not require a trust or direct connections between collaborators.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The need for internal audits to provide effective oversight of organizational efficiency will require a change in the way that information is accessed in new formats.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Blockchain adoption requires a framework to identify the risk of exposure associated with transactions using blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The Institute of Internal Auditors has identified the need for internal auditors to address this transformational technology.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] New methods are required to develop audit plans that identify threats and risks.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The Internal Audit Foundation study, *Blockchain and Internal Audit,* assesses these factors.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The American Institute of Certified Public Accountants has outlined new roles for auditors as a result of blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In blockchain technology, a **testnet** is an instance of a blockchain powered by the same or a newer version of the underlying software, to be used for testing and experimentation without risk to real funds or the main chain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Testnet coins are separate and distinct from the official *mainnet* coins, don't have value, and can be obtained freely from *faucets*.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Testnets allow for the development of blockchain applications without the risk of losing funds.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Using testnets, a bug was discovered in the Bitcoin Core software that gave miners the ability to take down essential parts of the Bitcoin infrastructure (nodes) by sending a 'bad' block to the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A **mainnet** (short for *main network*) is the fully operational version of a blockchain where real transactions occur, as opposed to a testnet.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] It is secured through consensus mechanisms like Proof of Work or Proof of Stake and supports smart contracts, token transfers, and decentralized applications.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] A *mainnet launch* marks the transition from a testnet to a live blockchain, involving security audits, network deployment, and token migration.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] In September 2015, the first peer-reviewed academic journal dedicated to cryptocurrency and blockchain technology research, *Ledger*, was announced.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The inaugural issue was published in December 2016.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The journal covers aspects of mathematics, computer science, engineering, law, economics and philosophy that relate to cryptocurrencies.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] The journal encourages authors to digitally sign a file hash of submitted papers, which are then timestamped into the bitcoin blockchain.
[src:sidechains/blockchain] Authors are also asked to include a personal bitcoin address on the first page of their papers for non-repudiation purposes.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] The Cosmos project was initiated in 2014 by Jae Kwon, who developed the Tendermint consensus algorithm.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] Ethan Buchman joined the project in 2015.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] In 2016, they published the white paper *"Cosmos: A Network of Distributed Ledgers"*, which proposed a network of independent blockchains connected through the Inter-Blockchain Communication (IBC) protocol.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] In April 2017, the Interchain Foundation conducted a token sale that raised approximately $17 million.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] The foundation is legally registered as Interchain Stiftung in the Canton of Zug, supervised by the Swiss Federal Foundation Supervisory Authority (Eidgenossische Stiftungsaufsicht).
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] The Cosmos Hub mainnet was launched on 13 March 2019.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] In 2021, the IBC protocol was introduced, enabling interoperability between independent blockchains.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] (operating as Tendermint Inc.) rebranded to Ignite.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] In February 2023, the Tendermint Core consensus software was forked and renamed CometBFT, maintained as an open-source project.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] The Cosmos stack refers to a set of open-source tools and protocols for building application-specific and interoperable blockchains.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] It includes a modular development framework (Cosmos SDK), a consensus engine (CometBFT), interoperability protocols such as the Inter-Blockchain Communication Protocol (IBC), and support for different execution environments and application-specific modules.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] Extensions to the stack include compatibility layers such as Cosmos EVM, as well as shared security mechanisms such as Interchain Security, which allows blockchains to leverage validator sets from other networks.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] Cosmos uses a proof-of-stake consensus mechanism based on the CometBFT Byzantine Fault Tolerance (BFT) engine, formerly known as Tendermint.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] The academic paper, *"The latest gossip on BFT consensus"* by Buchman, Kwon, and Milosevic (2018), presented the protocol's formal specification.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] A 2025 study provided a universally composable security analysis demonstrating the protocol's resilience against strategic message-delay attacks.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] The Cosmos SDK is framework for building application-specific blockchains and components customization.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] Blockchains built with the Cosmos SDK can interoperate via the IBC protocol, which enables the exchange of data and tokens without a central intermediary.
[src:sidechains/cosmos-network] In 2022, decentralized derivatives exchange dYdX announced it would migrate from Ethereum to a dedicated Cosmos-based blockchain, with the new chain launching in October 2023.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Forks are related to the fact that different parties need to use common rules to maintain the history of the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] When parties are not in agreement, alternative chains may emerge.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] While most forks are short-lived some are permanent.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Short-lived forks are due to the difficulty of reaching fast consensus in a distributed system.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Blockchain forks have been widely discussed in the context of the bitcoin scalability problem.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Forks can be classified as *accidental* or *intentional*.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] *Accidental fork* happens when two or more miners find a block at nearly the same time.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The fork is resolved when subsequent block(s) are added and one of the chains becomes longer than the alternative(s).
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The network abandons the blocks that are not in the longest chain (they are called *orphaned* blocks).
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] A *source code fork* or *project fork* is when developers take a copy of source code from one cryptocurrency project and start **independent** development on it, creating a separate and new piece of blockchain.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Such examples are; Litecoin a source code fork of Bitcoin, Monero fork of Bytecoin and Dogecoin fork of Litecoin.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] A *soft fork* is a backward-compatible change to the blockchain protocol that allows new rules to be introduced without requiring all users to upgrade their software.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] In a soft fork, a majority of the network’s miners implement the new rules and begin following the updated version of the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The rest of the network can continue to follow the blockchain, but they will be unable to validate that new blocks follow the updated rules.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Because a soft fork is backward-compatible, it does not result in the creation of a new blockchain or the splitting of the network.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Instead, it allows the network to gradually transition to the new rules while still maintaining compatibility with the old rules.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] A *permanent chain split* is described as a case when there are two or more permanent versions of a blockchain sharing the same history up to a certain time, after which the histories start to differ.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Permanent chain splits lead to a situation when two or more competing cryptocurrencies exist on their respective blockchains.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The taxation of cryptocurrency splits varies substantially from state to state.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The ATO does not classify cryptocurrency splits as taxation events.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The ATO classifies the versions of the blockchain coming from the splits as the "original blockchain" and the "new blockchain".
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] In relation to the cost base, the cryptocurrency on the original blockchain should be assigned all the original cost base, while the cryptocurrency on the new blockchain should be assigned cost base zero.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The UK HMRC does not classify cryptocurrency splits as taxation events.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] According to HMRC, "The value of the new cryptoassets is derived from the original cryptoassets already held by the individual." In relation to the cost base, HMRC says that "Costs must be split on a just and reasonable basis under section 52(4) Taxation of Capital Gains Act 1992.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] HMRC does not prescribe any particular apportionment method.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] As of September 2021, it is believed that more than 2.3 million people in the UK own a cryptoasset.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] As these assets do not physically exist, HMRC has been forced to issue guidance stating that cryptoassets will follow the residence of the beneficial owner.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] Residents in the UK who trade cryptoassets, no matter where these assets are "held", will be liable to UK taxes.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] However, there is a growing belief that this guidance may well be challenged in the courts.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] The US Internal Revenue Service (IRS) classifies cryptocurrency splits as "airdrops" and as taxable events.
[src:sidechains/fork-blockchain] According to the guidance published by IRS, provided the taxpayer is in possession of the keys, they are obliged to pay tax for the new cryptocurrency using the fair market value of the cryptocurrency as their income.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Designed to facilitate interoperability, Polkadot enables independent blockchains to exchange data and assets securely without relying on centralized intermediaries.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] This cross-chain communication framework allows for the development of decentralized applications (dApps) and services that span multiple blockchains within a unified network architecture.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Polkadot was created by the Ethereum co-founder Gavin Wood, Robert Habermeier and Peter Czaban.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] The white paper for Polkadot was published by Wood in 2016.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] The Polkadot SDK and other core technology components are being developed by Parity Technologies.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] The project raised over $144.3 million in its Initial coin offering in October 2017.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] In 2017, Gavin Wood, Aeron Buchanan, Peter Czaban, Reto Trinkler, and Mathias Bucher, established the Web3 Foundation, a non-profit organization based in Zug, Switzerland, to promote and provide funding for blockchain-based decentralized web technologies.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] The Polkadot SDK and other core technology components are being developed by Parity Technologies, a blockchain infrastructure company founded in 2015 by Gavin Wood and Jutta Steiner.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] In October 2017, Polkadot raised over $144.3 million in its initial coin offering (ICO).
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Shortly after the ICO, a vulnerability in the multi-signature wallets developed by Parity Technologies led to the freezing of approximately $150 million worth of Ethereum, including a significant portion of the funds raised.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Over 500 wallets were impacted, including Polkadot’s wallet, which held a significant portion of the $144.3 million raised during its ICO.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] In 2019, Polkadot raised an additional $43 million through a private token sale.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] In May 2020, Polkadot launched its mainnet under a proof-of-authority consensus model, managed by the Web3 Foundation during its early phase.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] By June 2020, the network transitioned to a Nominated Proof-of-Stake (NPoS) consensus mechanism, allowing token holders to nominate validators to secure the network and process transactions.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] In December 2021, Polkadot introduced parachain functionality, allowing multiple blockchains to run simultaneously and connect to the network's *Relay Chain*.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] In December 2024, Polkadot's canary network Kusama underwent a stress test known as "The Spammening," handling approximately 143,000 transactions per second (TPS) at just 23% capactiy.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Polkadot is founded on the premise that there will be a multitude of blockchains in the future.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] It provides an open-source software development kit called Polkadot SDK that can be used by development teams to build their own blockchains.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] These blockchains can function independently, known as "solochains," or integrate into the Polkadot network as "parachains," thereby benefiting from shared security and cross-chain communication capabilities.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Polkadot offers three properties to parachains: sovereignty, shared security and interoperability.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] XCMP is Polkadot's protocol for facilitating communication between parachains.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] It enables the transfer of arbitrary data across chains, supporting a wide range of applications, including token transfers, smart contract interactions, and more complex cross-chain operations.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] XCMP operates by allowing parachains to send messages to each other through the Relay Chain.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Polkadot implements an on-chain governance system, allowing stakeholders to influence the network's development and decision-making processes.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Over time, its governance model has transitioned from Governance V1 to OpenGov, to address concerns of decentralization and community involvement.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Polkadot Council members and *Relay Chain* Validators are selected via Phragmen election method.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] The network uses a nominated proof-of-stake consensus algorithm.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] The protocol used, Blind Assignment for Blockchain Extension (BABE), is derived from Ouroboros.
[src:sidechains/polkadot-blockchain-platform] Validators are responsible for block production and validation, while nominators support validators by staking DOT tokens on their behalf.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] A **smart contract** is a computer program or a transaction protocol that is intended to automatically execute, control or document events and actions according to the terms of a contract or an agreement.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The objectives of smart contracts are the reduction of need for trusted intermediators, arbitration costs, and fraud losses, as well as the reduction of malicious and accidental exceptions.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Smart contracts are commonly associated with cryptocurrencies, and the smart contracts introduced by Ethereum are generally considered a fundamental building block for decentralized finance (DeFi) and non-fungible token (NFT) applications.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The original Ethereum white paper by Vitalik Buterin in 2014 describes the Bitcoin protocol as a weak version of the smart contract concept as originally defined by Nick Szabo, and proposed a stronger version based on the Solidity language, which is Turing complete.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Since then, various cryptocurrencies have supported programming languages which allow for more advanced smart contracts between untrusted parties.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] A smart contract should not be confused with a smart legal contract, which is a traditional, natural-language, legally binding agreement that has selected terms expressed and implemented in machine-readable code.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] By 1996, Nick Szabo was using the term "smart contract" to refer to contracts which would be enforced by physical property (such as hardware or software) instead of by law.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Szabo described vending machines as an example of this concept.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In 1998, the term was used to describe objects in rights management service layer of the system *The Stanford Infobus*, which was a part of Stanford Digital Library Project.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] A *smart contract* does not typically constitute a valid binding agreement at law.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Proposals exist to regulate smart contracts.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Smart contracts are not legal agreements, but instead transactions which are executed automatically by a computer program or a transaction protocol, such as technological means for the automation of payment obligations such as by transferring cryptocurrencies or other tokens.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Some scholars have argued that the imperative or declarative nature of programming languages would impact the legal validity of smart contracts.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In some jurisdictions, legal scholars have examined how the rigidity of smart contracts interacts with traditional doctrines such as contractual unforeseeability.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Since the 2015 launch of the Ethereum blockchain, the term "smart contract" has been applied to general purpose computation that takes place on a blockchain.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The US National Institute of Standards and Technology describes a "smart contract" as a "collection of code and data (sometimes referred to as functions and state) that is deployed using cryptographically signed transactions on the blockchain network".
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In this interpretation a smart contract is any kind of computer program which uses a blockchain.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] A smart contract also can be regarded as a secured stored procedure, as its execution and codified effects (like the transfer of tokens between parties) cannot be manipulated without modifying the blockchain itself.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In this interpretation, the execution of contracts is controlled and audited by the platform, not by arbitrary server-side programs connecting to the platform.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In 2018, a US Senate report said: "While smart contracts might sound new, the concept is rooted in basic contract law.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Usually, the judicial system adjudicates contractual disputes and enforces terms, but it is also common to have another arbitration method, especially for international transactions.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] With smart contracts, a program enforces the contract built into the code." States in the US which have passed legislation on the use of smart contracts include Arizona, Iowa, Nevada, Tennessee, and Wyoming.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In April 2021, the UK Jurisdiction Taskforce (UKJT) published the Digital Dispute Resolution Rules (the Digital DR Rules), which were intended to enable the rapid resolution of blockchain and crypto legal disputes in Britain.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Similar to a transfer of value on a blockchain, deployment of a smart contract on a blockchain occurs by sending a transaction from a wallet for the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The transaction includes the compiled code for the smart contract as well as a special receiver address.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] That transaction must then be included in a block that is added to the blockchain, at which point the smart contract's code will execute to establish the initial state of the smart contract.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Byzantine fault-tolerant algorithms secure the smart contract in a decentralized way from attempts to tamper with it.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Once a smart contract is deployed, it cannot be updated.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Smart contracts on a blockchain can store arbitrary state and execute arbitrary computations.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] End clients interact with a smart contract through transactions.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Such transactions with a smart contract can invoke other smart contracts.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] These transactions might result in changing the state and sending coins from one smart contract to another or from one account to another.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The most popular blockchain for running smart contracts is Ethereum.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] On Ethereum, smart contracts are typically written in a Turing-complete programming language called Solidity, and compiled into low-level bytecode to be executed by the Ethereum Virtual Machine.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Due to the halting problem and other security problems, Turing-completeness is considered to be a risk and is deliberately avoided by languages like Vyper.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Some of the other smart contract programming languages missing Turing-completeness are Simplicity, Scilla, Ivy and Bitcoin Script.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Some newer platforms have explored "asset-oriented" domain-specific languages (such as Scrypto) that treat digital assets as native data types within the language environment to enforce finiteness and safety rules at the compiler level.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] However, measurements in 2020 using regular expressions showed that only 35.3% of 53,757 Ethereum smart contracts at that time included recursions and loops — constructs connected to the halting problem.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Several languages are designed to enable formal verification: Bamboo, IELE, Simplicity, Michelson (can be verified with Rocq), Liquidity (compiles to Michelson), Scilla, DAML and Pact.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Processes on a blockchain are generally deterministic in order to ensure Byzantine fault tolerance.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Nevertheless, real world application of smart contracts, such as lotteries and casinos, require secure randomness.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In fact, blockchain technology reduces the costs for conducting of a lottery and is therefore beneficial for the participants.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Randomness on blockchain can be implemented by using block hashes or timestamps, oracles, commitment schemes, special smart contracts like RANDAO and Quanta, as well as sequences from mixed strategy Nash equilibria.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] In 1998, Szabo proposed that smart contract infrastructure can be implemented by replicated asset registries and contract execution using cryptographic hash chains and Byzantine fault-tolerant replication.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Askemos implemented this approach in 2002 using Scheme (later adding SQLite) as the contract script language.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] One proposal for using Bitcoin for replicated asset registration and contract execution is called "colored coins".
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Replicated titles for potentially arbitrary forms of property, along with replicated contract execution, are implemented in different projects.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] As of 2015, UBS was experimenting with "smart bonds" that use the bitcoin blockchain in which payment streams could hypothetically be fully automated, creating a self-paying instrument.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Inheritance wishes could hypothetically be implemented automatically upon registration of a death certificate by means of smart contracts.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Birth certificates can also work together with smart contracts.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Chris Snook of *Inc.com* suggests smart contracts could also be used to handle real estate transactions and could be used in the field of title records and in the public register.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Seth Oranburg and Liya Palagashvili argue that smart contracts could also be used in employment contracts, especially temporary employment contracts, which according to them would benefit the employer.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The transactions data from a blockchain-based smart contract is visible to all users in the blockchain.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The data provides cryptographic view of the transactions, however, this leads to a situation where bugs, including security holes, are visible to all yet may not be quickly fixed.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Such an attack, difficult to fix quickly, was successfully executed on The DAO in June 2016, draining approximately US$50 million worth of Ether at the time, while developers attempted to come to a solution that would gain consensus.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] The DAO program had a time delay in place before the hacker could remove the funds; a hard fork of the Ethereum software was done to claw back the funds from the attacker before the time limit expired.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Other high-profile attacks include the Parity multisignature wallet attacks, and an integer underflow/overflow attack (2018), totaling over US$184 million.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Smart legal contracts are distinct from smart contracts.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] As mentioned above, a smart contract is not necessarily legally enforceable as a contract.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] On the other hand, a smart legal contract has all the elements of a legally enforceable contract in the jurisdiction in which it can be enforced and it can be enforced by a court or tribunal.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] Therefore, while every smart legal contract will contain some elements of a smart contract, not every smart contract will be a smart legal contract.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] There is no formal definition of a smart legal contract in the legal industry.
[src:sidechains/smart-contract] A Ricardian contract is a type of smart legal contract.
